cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SI, cs.MM, cs.CC 

This paper deals with information theory and communication systems, specifically the Gaussian interference channel and its variants. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also discusses multiple-access channels and Z-interference channels, which fall under the categories of cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), respectively. The paper also uses an incremental channel approach, which is a common technique in the field of cs.MM (Multimedia) for video and audio coding. Finally, the paper provides a proof of the "missing corner points" of the interference channel, which is related to coding theory and falls under the category of cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
